I. These workers later were also “imported” to the US and Canada as those countries joined the war and felt the need for additional labor. The work is based on a decade of archival research in China, Taiwan, France, Germany, the US, Canada, and Britain. It sheds light on these long-forgotten workers, who were instrumental in the Allied efforts that resulted in a defeat of Germany. Yet the persistent racism they encountered in the West, and ultimately the erasure of their contribution both by the countries they served and the Chinese elites who recruited them for the purpose, raises the question of how power determines who is included and excluded from the historical record.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aForeign workers, ChinesezEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xConscript laborzEurope. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xParticipation, Chinese. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zFrance. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674060555zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674060555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674060555/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK